Two authors examined 41 articles and identified 12 that met the inclusion criteria ( Table 1 ). The search strategy and flow diagram are presented using the PRISMA guidelines. Results focused on identifying definitions of atypical croup in the literature. The etiology, incidence, prevalence, diagnosis and management of atypical croup were secondary objectives. 2013) defined croup as atypical if symptoms lasted longer than seven days, although other studies did not provide a specific duration [16, 17] . Finally, croup associated with an uncommon pathogen was also defined as atypical. In a study by Low et al. (2012) , fungus was identified as the causative organism while Miller et al. (1982) reported a case of atypical croup caused by Chlamydia trachomatis [17] [18] [19] . 